<!-- Modal Deprecation -->
<details id="detail-modal">
  <summary>📋 Modal Deprecation <span class="winner-tag">pf-codemods WINS (partial)</span></summary>
  <div class="detail-content">
    <h4>What Changed in PF6</h4>
    <p>The legacy <code>Modal</code> API is deprecated. It's moved to <code>@patternfly/react-core/deprecated</code>. The new composable <code>Modal</code> (with <code>ModalHeader</code>, <code>ModalBody</code>, <code>ModalFooter</code>) is promoted from <code>@patternfly/react-core/next</code> to <code>@patternfly/react-core</code>.</p>
    <p>The full migration requires refactoring from the legacy API to the new composable API. Using the <code>/deprecated</code> import path is an acceptable transitional step.</p>
    
    <table>
      <tr><th>Aspect</th><th>pf-codemods</th><th>semver/goose</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Modal import updated?</td><td class="metric-warn">Partially — moved to /deprecated path</td><td class="metric-bad">No change</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Composable Modal refactor?</td><td class="metric-bad">No</td><td class="metric-bad">No</td></tr>
      <tr><td>File affected</td><td>TimeRangeDropdown.tsx</td><td>—</td></tr>
    </table>
    
    <p><strong>pf-codemods</strong> at least acknowledged the deprecation by moving the import. This is a valid transitional step per the <a href="https://www.patternfly.org/get-started/upgrade/">PF6 Upgrade Guide</a>. <strong>semver/goose</strong> left the Modal import unchanged — however, since Modal was not imported from <code>/deprecated</code> on <code>main</code> either, this means the main branch's Modal usage is actually the <em>new promoted</em> Modal API that was promoted from <code>/next</code>. The pf-codemods branch may have <strong>regressed</strong> the Modal by moving it to <code>/deprecated</code> when it was already using the promoted version.</p>
    
    <h4>⚠️ Critical Nuance</h4>
    <p>On the <code>main</code> branch, <code>Modal</code> is imported from <code>@patternfly/react-core</code> (the promoted new API). The pf-codemods branch moved it to <code>@patternfly/react-core/deprecated</code> (the old API). This may actually be a <strong>regression</strong> rather than progress, since the code was already using the new composable children (<code>ModalBody</code>, <code>ModalFooter</code>, <code>ModalHeader</code>).</p>
    <p>Both branches still import <code>ModalBody</code>, <code>ModalFooter</code>, <code>ModalHeader</code> from <code>@patternfly/react-core</code> — these are the new API components. The pf-codemods branch creates a confusing split where <code>Modal</code> comes from <code>/deprecated</code> but its children come from the main path.</p>
    <p>Given this analysis, pf-codemods' Modal change is at best a wash and at worst a regression. Points awarded are minimal.</p>
  </div>
</details>

<!-- Select onSelect Type -->
<details id="detail-select">
  <summary>🎯 Select onSelect Type Signature <span class="winner-tag">semver/goose WINS</span></summary>
  <div class="detail-content">
    <h4>What Changed in PF6</h4>
    <p>The <code>Select</code> component's <code>onSelect</code> callback changed its <code>value</code> parameter type. In PF6, it uses <code>SelectOptionProps['value']</code> (which is <code>string | number | undefined</code>) instead of a simple <code>string</code> or <code>string | number</code>.</p>
    
    <h4>Before (main)</h4>
    <pre><code>// AdvancedSearchForm.tsx
onSelect={(_e, value: string) =&gt; { ... }}

// TimeUnitPicker.tsx
onSelect={(_: ReactMouseEvent&lt;Element, MouseEvent&gt;, value: string | number) =&gt; { ... }}</code></pre>
    
    <h4>After (semver/goose)</h4>
    <pre><code>// AdvancedSearchForm.tsx
import { SelectOptionProps } from '@patternfly/react-core';
onSelect={(_e, value: SelectOptionProps['value']) =&gt; { ... }}

// TimeUnitPicker.tsx
import { SelectOptionProps } from '@patternfly/react-core';
onSelect={(_: ReactMouseEvent&lt;Element, MouseEvent&gt;, value: SelectOptionProps['value']) =&gt; { ... }}</code></pre>
    
    <table>
      <tr><th>Aspect</th><th>pf-codemods</th><th>semver/goose</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Select type fix applied?</td><td class="metric-bad">No</td><td class="metric-good">Yes — 2 files</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Correct PF6 type used?</td><td>—</td><td class="metric-good">Yes — <code>SelectOptionProps['value']</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Import added?</td><td>—</td><td class="metric-good">Yes — <code>SelectOptionProps</code></td></tr>
    </table>
    <p class="footnote">This change aligns the code with the PF6 <code>Select</code> API type signature, preventing potential type mismatches when stricter TypeScript checking is enabled.</p>
  </div>
</details>

